Graphical Representation and Important Assumptions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
See Appendix A-1 for a graphical representation.
 Carefully note the axes of the graph.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also note that because of the assumptions that we placed on expected utility
 functions of the two types of consumers, the expected utility functions
 satisfy the single crossing principle: 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall\vec{s_{i}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{\partial s_{2i}}{\partial s_{1i}}=-\frac{(1-p_{i})u'(s_{1i})}{p_{i}u'(s_{2i})},\]

\end_inset

which is how we calculated the Marginal Rate of Substitution in Econ 2020a.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
If you can't remember, go back to my section notes from Econ 2020a on the
 Implicit Function Theorem.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Therefore, we see that at every point 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{s_{i}}$
\end_inset

 in the graph shown in Appendix A-1, the slope of the level set through
 such point is greater for the good type than the bad type.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, I've drawn in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

suns
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for the graph in A-1.
 Can you figure out why they were placed in their respective positions?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For the firm, 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
\mathbb{E}\left[\pi\right] & = & p_{i}(M-R)+(1-p_{i})(M)\\
 & = & p_{i}(W-L-s_{2})+(1-p_{i})(W-s_{1})\\
 & = & \left(W-p_{i}L\right)-\left(p_{i}s_{2}+(1-p_{i})s_{1}\right)\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where the first term is equal to the uninsured expected consumption and
 the second term is equal to the insured expected consumption.
 We can reorganize this as:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
s_{2}=-\frac{\left(1-p_{i}\right)}{p_{i}}s_{1}+\frac{1}{p_{i}}\cdot\left\{ \left(W-p_{i}L\right)-\mathbb{E}\left[\pi\right]\right\} \label{linear iso profit}\end{equation}

\end_inset

which shows us that the iso profit lines are linear in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[s_{1},s_{2}\right]$
\end_inset

 Euclidean space and profit is increasing towards the sun in Appendix A-1.
 
\end_layout

